# khaledzaky.com — Project Rules

## Project Overview
Personal website and blog for Khaled Zaky (Senior Director, Agentic AI Platform Engineering at RBC Borealis).
Built with Astro v5 + Tailwind CSS v4. Deployed on AWS via CodeBuild → S3 → CloudFront.
Repo: https://github.com/kzaky/khaledzaky.com (branch: master)

---

## AI Blog Agent — Architecture Constants

### Lambda Functions (10 total)
Pipeline order: `research → draft → verify → chart → notify → [HITL] → publish`
Full list: `research`, `draft`, `verify`, `chart`, `notify`, `approve`, `publish`, `ingest`, `upload`, `alarm-formatter`

### LLM Passes Per Lambda
**Research Lambda (7 Haiku + Sonnet passes):**
1. Query generation — Haiku
2. Perplexity query reshape — Haiku (overlaps Tavily search)
3. Editorial hooks extraction — Haiku (parallel with thinking plan)
4. Thinking plan — Sonnet + extended thinking (parallel with editorial hooks)
5. Research synthesis — Sonnet
6. Cross-reference fact-check — Haiku
7. Chart data extraction — Haiku

**Draft Lambda (7 passes: 2 Sonnet + 5 Haiku):**
1. Thinking/drafting plan — Sonnet + extended thinking (`budget_tokens: 2000`)
2. Full draft generation — Sonnet
3. Chart placeholder insertion — Haiku
4. Diagram placeholder insertion — Haiku
5. Citation audit — Haiku
6. Voice profile audit — Haiku
7. Insight audit — Haiku (skips posts >2500 words)

**Verify Lambda:** variable Haiku calls (one per external URL)

**Total per post: ~14 LLM calls**

### Cost Estimate
- Per post: ~$0.17 (~$0.16 Bedrock + ~$0.01 Perplexity)
- At 4 posts/month: ~$0.65/month
- At 10 posts/month: ~$1.60/month

### SSM Parameter Keys
- `/blog-agent/github-token` — GitHub PAT (SecureString)
- `/blog-agent/tavily-api-key` — Tavily search (SecureString)
- `/blog-agent/perplexity-api-key` — Perplexity sonar-pro (SecureString, optional — degrades gracefully)
- `/blog-agent/upload-passphrase` — /drop page auth (SecureString)
- `/blog-agent/known-post-slugs` — String, kept current by Publish Lambda
- `cloudfront_distid` — CloudFront distribution ID (String, used by CodeBuild)

### Models
- **Sonnet:** `us.anthropic.claude-sonnet-4-6` — creative passes (thinking + full draft)
- **Haiku:** `us.anthropic.claude-haiku-4-5-20251001-v1:0` — all deterministic passes

### Annotation Types (stripped by Publish Lambda before commit)
- `<!-- ⚠️ CITATION FAIL: ... -->` — hard citation failure
- `<!-- 💡 CITATION NOTE: ... -->` — soft citation concern
- `<!-- ⚡ INSIGHT: ... -->` — generic paragraph flagged by insight audit

### Key Files
- `agent/README.md` — full agent documentation
- `agent/template.yaml` — CloudFormation (all Lambda + Step Functions resources)
- `agent/deploy.sh` — one-command deployment
- `agent/voice-profile.md` — author voice guide (loaded from S3 at runtime)
- `agent/tests/test_handlers.py` — smoke tests; LAMBDA_DIRS must include all 10 Lambdas
- `RECOVERY.md` — disaster recovery runbook
- `README.md` — root project documentation

### Infrastructure Notes
- CloudFormation stack: `blog-agent` (us-east-1)
- `DraftsBucketPolicy` managed outside CFN — do NOT add to template
- `ApproveApiRoute` is a single GET route — do NOT split into GET/POST
- CSP `connect-src` managed via CloudFront CLI (not CFN) — drift is intentional
- `infra/template.yaml` CSP is intentionally behind deployed state

---

## Documentation Invariants
When making ANY pipeline change, these must stay in sync:
1. Lambda count (10) referenced in `README.md`, `agent/README.md`, `template.yaml` comments
2. LLM call count and cost estimates in both READMEs
3. Module docstrings in affected `index.py` files
4. `agent/tests/test_handlers.py` → `LAMBDA_DIRS` list
5. `RECOVERY.md` → SSM secrets section + log retention loop
6. `agent/deploy.sh` → packaging loop, deploy loop, cleanup line, prerequisites

---

## Blog Post Tone
Khaled is a software and platform engineer learning the AI/ML space — NOT a deep academic expert.
Posts should sound like:
- Weekend research + curiosity, not authoritative treatises
- Personal reflection from 9-5 work experience
- "I've been thinking about..." not "It is well established that..."
- Explain jargon when used (e.g., MMLU needs a plain-English parenthetical)
- Avoid: BLEU, ROUGE, and other benchmarks the author doesn't claim to know deeply

---

## Commit Format
Use conventional commits:
- `feat:` new features
- `fix:` bug fixes
- `docs:` documentation only
- `refine:` editorial/tone changes to blog posts
- `infra:` infrastructure/CloudFormation changes
- `chore:` maintenance (deps, cleanup)

Always push to `master` after committing.
